AB  - Vulture populations in India have been reduced by the occurrence of diclofenac poisoning, habitat degradation and climatic variation. An effective assessment of the status of Indian vultures requires a methodology including literature study, field research and the mapping of the changing ranges and habitat distributions of the various species. This chapter investigates the evidence for the decline of vulture populations in India, taking a case study of Central India, a stronghold for vulture populations. The study is based on a survey of the literature on vulture population counts, ranging and habitat mapping and predictive models of vulture presence. It investigates the status of endangered vulture species, their conservation requirements, the data collection methodologies and technology required for such assessments. Maps of vulture distribution and ecological relations are presented and discussed. Vulture conservation policies are also explored. © 2018 Nova Science Publishers, Inc.
