AB  - The cooperative marine autonomous system (MAS), a combination of an autonomous surface vehicle (ASV) with an autonomous underwater vehicle (AUV), would provide researchers, governments, and conservationists unprecedented reach to study the marine environment and prepare for the effects of climate change. Ideally, these systems would be inexpensive and highly adaptable to build a network similar to that of the National Data Buoy Center, providing a complementary view of the world's oceans. To achieve this degree of proliferation, this paper discusses the fusion of a commercially available ASV, the C-Worker 6 (ASV Global, LLC, Portland, OR, USA) with the bio-inspired vehicle (BIV) (Aquaai Corporation, San Diego, CA, USA). The first, intended application for this system is performing coral reef photogrammetric studies. In this role, the ASV acts as a mobile base station for one to four individual BIVs; providing long-range transport between survey locations, battery recharging, data relay, and improved underwater navigational accuracy to the BIV via GPS-to-USBL communications. The BIV(s) then act(s) as extensions to the ASV's sensor network, providing imaging as well as in situ temperature, conductivity, and pressure data. This article examines the design challenges (and proposes solutions) associated with docking the BIV with the ASV as well as a reliable, safe power transfer mechanism for recharging the BIV. At the time of writing, the BIV and docking bay are under development, while the principle of improving underwater navigational accuracy using a MAS has been tested through a collaboration between ASV Global and the National Oceanographic Centre (Southampton, UK) (see Oceans 2017 Proceedings, Autonomous Surface/Sub-surface Survey System for further information). © 2017 Marine Technology Society.
